\par\par \b \uc2  A flexible  \highlight22\uc2 budget \highlight\uc2  needed to respond to changes. \b0\par\par\uc2 907 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 January 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The government presented on Tuesday its draft \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the 1999/2000 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. It balances at Rp 218.2 trillion (US$29 billion), a 17.3 percent drop from the current \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Pande Raja Silalahi discusses the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 's value and its potential impact on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Question: What do you think of the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  proposed by President B.J. Habibie before the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  on Tuesday? \par \par \uc2  Pande: Looking at the 1999/2000 draft \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a whole, some of its elements are too optimistic, some are realistic and others are pessimistic. Thus, the general perception of the draft \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is mixed. \par \par \uc2  Overly optimistic, I think, is the government's target on both income and value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which is 57 percent higher than in this \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . In a contracting \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , or in an \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  with zero growth, it is unrealistic to target increasing revenue from income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Even for companies which could really perform, they would not be able to book a drastic increase in income. Moreover, for companies suffering greatly in the crisis, they would not contribute anything to the government from income \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  because they would continue to book losses. \par \par \uc2  Nevertheless, I consider the assumptions used to draft the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  realistic enough. These include the zero growth for 1999/2000, inflation at 17 percent and the rupiah at 7,500 to the dollar. But, again, those assumptions are subject to change as they contain \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The rupiah's exchange rate, for instance, is prone to change because it is heavily influenced by psychology and perceptions on the currency. \par \par \uc2  But the government's revenue target for oil and gas is quite pessimistic, especially revenues from natural gas, because gas prices do not fall drastically and could rebound again at anytime. \par \par \uc2  And the big question mark surrounds foreign loans. Could we get that much (Rp 77.4 trillion)? \par \par \uc2  In this \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation, what we need is a flexible \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . If a particular target could not be achieved, we would know exactly the \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  in what sector needs to be cut. Conversely, if income suddenly exceeds projections due to improving oil or gas prices, for instance, we would also know what areas we have to push forward. These things need to be discussed by the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , together with the government. \par \par \uc2  Q: What about the \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  side of the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 ? \par \par \uc2  P: I agree with the government's proposal to raise civil servants' salaries and cut \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially on fuels. \par \par \uc2  An increase in civil servants' salaries will be positive. Just look at inflation, which last year alone soared 77 percent. It significantly cut civil servants' real income. How can they work well to serve the people if their real income has dropped sharply? At the same time, this reform era demands no more corruption in the civil service. Even a 30 percent increase in civil servants' salary is still far from enough to improve their real income. That will remain a problem, anyway. \par \par \uc2  The reduction of fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , I think, is a must. Although politically it is not good, economically it is welcome. The important thing is how to raise fuel prices proportionally so that it would not jerk up prices of related goods and services. Yes, price increases are normal consequences of the lifting of \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . We cannot eliminate this. But we can reduce the level of the increases or their impact on society through sufficient preparation. The problem is that we often eliminate \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  without sufficient preparation. Most recent was the removal of the fertilizer \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which caused political shocks. \par \par \uc2  Q: The reform government has again paid more attention to cooperatives and small enterprises in the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . How does this work for the country? \par \par \uc2  P: We do have to empower small and medium businesses. And we have to side with them because so far the holding of productive assets has been dominated by a minority. This has destroyed the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  itself, and so we have to correct this imbalance. But we have to pursue this through market-friendly ways, not through a Robin Hood approach, stealing from the rich and giving to the poor. We have to be realistic by asking ourselves why the enterprises are small. We have to be honest on whether we can help them to become medium size, and then big and bigger. If we examine them realistically, we will see that one of their main problems is not bank \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but the availability of bank credits. It is simple, actually. We can help them without giving them big \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  on \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Q: Unlike in the previous years, the government now proposes a contraction in development \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  from Rp 92.68 trillion this \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year to Rp 83.65 trillion. Do you think this meager amount is enough to stimulate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities? \par \par \uc2  P: It's difficult. The government's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for development \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  is actually even smaller, because the figure includes Rp 18 trillion set aside for the bank recapitalization program. Unquestionably, there is Rp 66 trillion left for real development \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . That is less than 10 percent of our gross domestic product, which is why the government is targeting zero percent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth for the 1999/2000 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. What is important now is how to spend every rupiah from the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to stimulate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities. (rid) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv16001kw\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
