ighlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, an inflation rate of 17 percent, and an exchange rate of Rp 7,500 to the U.S. dollar. Some believe the assumptions are too optimistic, particularly in these times of political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Economists have said that the income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and value added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue targets cannot be obtained with the current anemic condition of the business sector and declining bank deposit \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  receipts for the 1998/1999 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year are expected to exceed the target, mainly due to the high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  particularly in the second quarter of last year. \par \par \uc2  Many businessmen and industry associations have been lobbying President B.J. Habibie to grant \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  breaks to help them weather the current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  storm. \par \par \uc2  The latest attempt came from Investment Minister Hamzah Haz, who said in December last year that a Presidential Decree spelling out the criteria for \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  breaks for certain investments would immediately be issued, and become effective in January 1999. \par \par \uc2  He explained that the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  break facility was needed to attract foreign investment into the country, as it was faced with tight competition from other crisis-hit nations in the region. \par \par \uc2  Approved foreign direct investment between January and Dec. 15, 1998, dropped by more than 60 percent, to $13.3 billion, from $33.83 billion in the same period in 1997. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  office, however, hopes the \b \highlight22\uc2 ta