\par\par \b \uc2  Shoe producers predict exports down this year. \b0\par\par\uc2 660 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 January 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Local shoe producers foresee a continuing drop in export orders to US$1.5 billion this year from $1.8 billion in 1998 as foreign buyers anticipate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political instability in Indonesia, an industry executive has said. \par \par \uc2  The Secretary General of the Indonesian Footwear Association (Aprisindo), Djimanto, said last week buyers were concerned that \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in a country that has been rocked by tumultuous events would hamper producers' ability to get their shoes delivered on time. \par \par \uc2  "Export orders may fall because of trade financing problems and vulnerable security, and buyers doubt we can deliver our orders on time," Djimanto told The Jakarta Post after an exporters meeting with top government officials on trade financing. \par \par \uc2  As the year commences, several scattered outbreaks of unrest across the country have already brought more international attention to Indonesia, further discouraging buyers from ordering from the country, he said. \par \par \uc2  Djimanto said shoe exports had been going downhill since the beginning of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in mid 1997, causing local producers with heavy reliance on imported materials to stagger under the weight of trade financing problems. \par \par \uc2  Locally issued letters of credit were rejected by international banks as confidence in the country's banks eroded. \par \par \uc2  Later, after the government secured financial guarantees to encourage the international banks to accept the locally-issued L/Cs, local banks still required producers to deposit cash to the value of the L/Cs before the issuance. \par \par \uc2  This is a burden for many cash-strapped companies, while banks have frozen credits due to a tight money \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  But it was not until the second half of 1998 that exports were further dragged down by a series of politically and nonpolitically motivated outbreaks of social unrest, starting with the bloody May riots in Jakarta which led president Soeharto to resign. \par \par \uc2  Topping off the disasters is an emerging phenomenon of robberies on inter-city roads of trucks carrying products to be delivered or exported. \par \par \uc2  "Since the change in the presidency, followed by endless local and international media exposure of riots things had gotten worse," Djimanto said. \par \par \uc2  Many subcontracting orders have now moved to the more competitive China, Indonesia's long-term rival in the shoe industry. \par \par \uc2  Foreign investors are now setting up new shoe factories in Vietnam instead of Indonesia, he said. \par \par \uc2  Some large brands have had reduced orders, while others have shifted their orders to foreign-invested companies producing in the country. \par \par \uc2  Shoes produced by foreign-invested companies, totaling 50 factories, contributed 50 percent of the country's total exports of footwear, he said. \par \par \uc2  "The foreign-invested companies suffer less damage from trade financing problems because they get help from their mother companies," he said. \par \par \uc2  Many local factories have closed down, he said. Aprisindo, which was 170-members strong before the crisis, now only has a membership of 107 companies, he said. \par \par \uc2  Some factories completely closed down, while some temporarily ceased production and were taking a wait and see stand, he said. \par \par \uc2  Djimanto said many of the local producers collapsed because they had relied solely on one large brand buyer. \par \par \uc2  On the other hand, the less affected local producers supply two or three smaller buyers per factory, so that they did not rely on one particular buyer, he said. \par \par \uc2  These producers, however, were expected to be more flexible with the design of their footwear products, he said. \par \par \uc2  The domestic market for sports and formal shoes was now "dead" because of diminishing buying power, but the market for casual sandals or half sandals has flourished and some producers even export them to Malaysia, he said. \par \par \uc2  Djimanto said Aprisindo had been inviting foreign buyers to visit footwear factories in the country to ensure them that prompt delivery was guaranteed. \par \par \uc2  "But as conditions become more \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  the buyers are scared to come to the country now, so we have to go and meet them in their respective countries," he added. (das) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv1l0021r\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
