\par\par \b \uc2  Banking on justice. \b0\par\par\uc2 635 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 January 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Although almost all agree that setting right the crippled banking industry is crucial to lead the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  out of its crisis, the government's bank recapitalization scheme is facing stiff opposition from most analysts and the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The proposed allocation of Rp 18 trillion of the 1999/2000 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the program has come under fire during deliberations in the House, even from the dominant Golkar faction noted mostly for simply toeing the official line. \par \par \uc2  It is extremely unfortunate that the element of the draft \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  provoking the greatest controversy is the bank recapitalization plan so crucial for the eventual recovery of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  But the voice of dissent in the legislature is understandable on a number of points. \par \par \uc2  The bone of contention against the recapitalization plan is not as much the amount of the costs as the botched handling of the banking crisis since early last year. It inevitably eroded whatever little \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  confidence remained in the government's ability to cope fairly and transparently with the moribund banking sector. The lack of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  trust has made it extremely difficult for the government to make a better \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  case of the urgent need for recapitalizing ailing banks. \par \par \uc2  There are, we think, several perplexing questions which must first to be straightened out to make the proposal palatable to taxpayers who bear the brunt of recapitalization costs. \par \par \uc2  Foremost among them is why capital standards for the program were set so low - covering institutions with capital adequacy ratios (CAR) ranging from minus 25 percent to 4 percent - that more than 80 banks would qualify for a total recapitalization of about Rp 300 trillion. \par \par \uc2  This lenient standard will not likely bolster confidence, both domestic and foreign, in the recapitalized banks since the international minimum capital standard is already 8 percent. Quite the contrary, given the enormous risks inherent in the continuing political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the questionable auditing standards in Indonesia, the minimum CAR should instead be set higher than the international level. \par \par \uc2  Moreover, in view of the extreme lack of technical competence in banking supervision, one of the main reasons behind the banking crisis in the first place, the number of banks should be made much smaller than current 200. The risk of failure in bailing out so many banks is surely much bigger than focusing limited resources on salvaging the few with strong management and high integrity. \par \par \uc2  The government may argue that raising the capital standard requirement would put most banks into liquidation at a huge cost and a big risk of triggering a new wave of massive runs on almost all banks, including those already with more than 4 percent CAR. \par \par \uc2  But pumping another Rp 300 trillion into so many ailing banks, on top of the Rp 116 trillion they still owe in emergency liquidity support from the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , would be a grave affront to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 's sense of justice. It raises the question whether the government is protecting depositors or simply bailing out bank shareholders, many of whom are accused of violating the legal lending limits and perceived to be engaged in underhanded relationships with political leaders or key officials. \par \par \uc2  The sense of justice also requires the government not only to disclose but deal firmly with those - be they directors or borrowers - responsible for bankrupting the six state banks now needing more than Rp 136 billion in recapitalization in order to survive. \par \par \uc2  Finance minister Bambang Subianto's warning that if the banks are not recapitalized the impact could be disastrous makes plain \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sense. But recapitalizing so many ailing banks, including those whose management and shareholders are notorious for their lack of integrity, is not only economically insensible and highly risky, but also a gross imposition on taxpayers ultimately footing the bill. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv1m0023i\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
