\par\par \b \uc2  Market to remain bearish despite Miyazawa aid. \b0\par\par\uc2 532 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 February 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  9 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Heightening political tension will continue to cast a shadow over trading on the Jakarta Stock Exchange after a new loan commitment from Japan failed to reverse the bearishness of the local market last week. \par \par \uc2  Stock analysts said lingering political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  and fear of mounting unrest ahead of the general election in June meant the embattled stock market would remain highly volatile. \par \par \uc2  In such an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation, they said, the market would overlook positive signs such as the decision of the Japanese government to extend US$2.4 billion in loans to Indonesia under the Miyazawa Plan. \par \par \uc2  "The positive impact of the Japanese commitment was short-lived because investors remain worried about the country's medium and long-term prospects," Fitri Murniati, a securities analysts with BNI Securities, said. \par \par \uc2  An institutional sales broker with Mashill Jaya Securities, Antonio Yongnata, agreed, saying the outlook of the local stock market had not changed and share prices would continue to remain under pressure. \par \par \uc2  Fitri added that share prices would remain very volatile this week because of profit taking by some investors. \par \par \uc2  Such a sharp volatility in share prices would force most investors to change their investment strategy from long-term investments to short-term speculative trading. \par \par \uc2  "Basically there are no more long-term investors here," Fitri said. \par \par \uc2  An institutional sales broker with Trimegah Securindolestari, Vonny Juwono, said the lack of long-term investors had caused daily trading volume on the local market to decline sharply to around Rp 150 billion ($17 million) from Rp 400 billion several months ago. \par \par \uc2  "Most investors prefer to take a wait and see attitude and are still closely watching the country's efforts to emerge from the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis," she said. \par \par \uc2  However, BNI's Fitri said certain stocks on the local bourse still offered investors some profit opportunities, especially blue-chip stocks with high liquidity and stocks in export-oriented companies. \par \par \uc2  She warned, however, that potential profit opportunities would be capped if the government raised \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The benchmark rate of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's one month promissory note rose slightly to 36.97 percent last week from 36.53 percent the previous week. \par \par \uc2  Increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  harm the stock market because investors prefer to invest in the money market when the \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  rise, Fitri said. \par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX) Composite Index fell 6.39 points to close at 405.55 last week, down from 410.55 the previous week. \par \par \uc2  Daily average turnover was 309.6 million shares last week compared to 250 million shares the previous week. \par \par \uc2  Daily average transaction value dropped to Rp 259.04 billion last week from Rp 267.88 billion the previous week. \par \par \uc2  Financial analysts and currency dealers said the fate of the rupiah, which managed to hit a weekly high of 8,450 against the dollar on Wednesday, would not improve because sentiment on the local currency remained bearish. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah closed 4 percent higher at 8,700 against the greenback on Friday, compared to its 9,050 close the previous week. \par \par \uc2  Most dealers said they expected the local unit would be traded between 8,500 and 9,000. (aly) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv28002do\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  IMF - Rupiah has to strengthen. \b0\par\par\uc2 204 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 February 1999\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The International Monetary Fund director for Asia-Pacific Hubert Neiss said that the weakened rupiah over the past few days was more due to social-political factors. \par \par \uc2  "If stability could be maintained and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  work, the rupiah should be able to strengthen. If the rupiah is overly depreciated, it should return to normal," said Neiss after meeting President B.J. Habibie. \par \par \uc2  Neiss said the weakened rupiah at this time has nothing to do with the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . "It has to do with domestic socio-political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  due to the worsening security situation," he said. \par \par \uc2  Neiss said his is optimistic that the rupiah will strengthen in the near future to the Rp 8,000 level to the dollar. The government sets for 1999/2000 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  a dollar at Rp 7,500. \par \par \uc2  In the meantime, the rupiah weakened on Monday to the USD to RP 8,850, following weaker yen. "The news spread in the market that big hedge funds bough US dollar against regional currencies. The rupiah weakened although it did not reach Rp 9,000 level. Yen again weakened to 113 to the dollar from 111," said a dealer at a joint venture bank. \par \par \uc2  (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010901dv290010u\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
