\par\par \b \uc2  Bearish mood overseas will cloud local market. \b0\par\par\uc2 584 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 February 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Stock trading on the local market will likely languish again this week as most investors, especially from the regional market, will be on holiday to celebrate the Chinese New Year, stock analysts said. \par \par \uc2  Several regional stock markets such as Hong Kong and Singapore will be closed for three days for the lunar holiday celebration scheduled to fall on Feb. 17. \par \par \uc2  As a result, trading activities on the country's hammered market will slow, they said. \par \par \uc2  An institutional sales broker with Trimegah Securindolestari, Vonny Juwono, said "Trading activities will be quiet in the coming week with a strong tendency to slow down." \par \par \uc2  Stockbrokers said that the daily trading volume in the local beleaguered bourse, which has dwindled to a meager Rp 150 billion compared to Rp 400 billion in boom times, would continue to plunge as the absence of fresh support from the domestic market further dampened market sentiment. \par \par \uc2  Stock analysts said lingering worries over the political development in the country, coupled with escalating fears of social unrest in the lead-up to the June general election still pose a major problems for foreign investors to reenter the local market. \par \par \uc2  Bahana Securities Andre Cita's head of sales said "Share prices will remain volatile, moving up and down to follow the trend in other markets." \par \par \uc2  Mashill Jaya Securities' head of research, Edhi S Widjojo, said that certain domestic investors would take a wait-and-see attitude and watch closely on the progress of the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political programs to bring the country out of its crisis. \par \par \uc2  "Things are very unpredictable now, with most investors watching closely on macroeconomic developments, the fate of the rupiah and political events in the country," he said. \par \par \uc2  Stock analysts said the high interest environment, which the government has pledged will remain in place until \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  have abated, would further dampen market sentiment as investors switch to the money market to take advantage of high investment returns in time deposits. \par \par \uc2  The interest rate on \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  one-month promissory notes (SBIs) rose to 37.15 percent on Wednesday last week from 36.59 percent the previous week. \par \par \uc2  "This high interest climate will kill investor sentiment in the equity market," Edhi added. \par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Stock Exchange composite price index fell 1.2 percent to 400.55 last week from 405.55 the previous week. \par \par \uc2  The daily average turnover fell sharply to 198.80 million shares last week compared to 309.6 million the previous week. \par \par \uc2  The daily average transaction value dropped to Rp 200.96 billion last week from Rp 259.04 billion the previous week. \par \par \uc2  Financial analyst and currency dealers said the rupiah, which closed unchanged at 8,700 against the U.S. dollar last week, would not improve much despite the increase in the \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  of SBIs last week. \par \par \uc2  Dealers said that although other regional markets like Hong Kong and Singapore would be closed for the Chinese New Year this week, the rupiah would not improve as it would futile for the rupiah to gain ground in this dire \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political crisis. \par \par \uc2  "If the rupiah strengthens to the 8,000 level, for example, offshore operators will benefit because they will buy the dollar at that level and the rupiah will succumb again," a dealer said. \par \par \uc2  Currency dealers said that the rupiah was expected to be traded in a range of between 8,500 and 8,800 against the dollar this week. (aly) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv2f002vg\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Seda - Government policies unclear. \b0\par\par\uc2 297 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 February 1999\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Presidential adviser on financial matters, Frans Seda, has accused the government of not having a grand design to overcome the present crisis. \par \par \uc2  This, he added here yesterday, could prolong the crisis and cause the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to contract by 3% and bring inflation to 30%. \par \par \uc2  Seda said that in overcoming the crisis the government has prepared four main policies, namely the social safety net program (JPS); restructurization of private banks; promoting the people's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; and bolster exports. \par \par \uc2  "In practice, the four policies are not managed in an integrated way but in a sectoral way," said Frans. \par \par \uc2  The failure of JPS, he said, was due to its ad hoc nature. \par \par \uc2  "Money is doled out here, money is doled out there," he said here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  He called for improvement of the JPS program so that people would not be hampered by administrative matters. \par \par \uc2  "JPS is designed to help the poor, not those with IDs." \par \par \uc2  Seda hinted that the JPS program has been mismanaged as there are officials who wish to take advantage of it. \par \par \uc2  "If that was not the case, how could the distribution be so bad?" he wondered. \par \par \uc2  As such, he added, while the World Bank would not halt its loans, it would only give under strict conditions. \par \par \uc2  On boosting exports, Seda said that the government only talks but does little despite th