\par\par \b \uc2  RI  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  recovery shaky - WB. \b0\par\par\uc2 706 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 March 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The World Bank predicted on Wednesday that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would shrink a minor 1 percent in the 1999/2000 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year before returning to modest growth of 3 percent in the following year, but only if the government sticks to its reform program. \par \par \uc2  If the government slows down on pushing through reform and the global situation also worsens, Indonesia's gross domestic product would dip by 3 percent next \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year, beginning in April, and remain stagnant in the following year. \par \par \uc2  "Indonesia's prospects are subject to a wider-than-usual band of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," the bank said in its country assistance strategy progress report. \par \par \uc2  "The point at which the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will bottom out and start growing again is hard to predict." \par \par \uc2  Part of the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the bank said, lay in Indonesia's main markets in East Asia and also in continued political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  at home. \par \par \uc2  A reversal in the world equity market and a deepening recession in Japan - Indonesia's main trading partner and source of investment - would seriously affect the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, it added. \par \par \uc2  The report warned the country's recession would be prolonged and recovery postponed if domestic political events took a turn for the worse. \par \par \uc2  "Nevertheless, if political events go smoothly and the government implements the reform program speedily and consistently, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will bottom out in the 2000/2001 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year." \par \par \uc2  The turnaround in growth is expected to come from agriculture - partly a rebound from last year's drought - mining and exports of labor intensive manufacturing. \par \par \uc2  The bank predicted inflation should moderate to 20 percent next \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year and 10 percent the following year, from almost 80 percent in the 1998 calendar year. \par \par \uc2  The government should continue with its tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to reduce inflation and stabilize the rupiah, the bank said. \par \par \uc2  It forecast Indonesia would continue enjoying a trade surplus of 3.2 percent of the GDP next \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year and 2.4 percent the following year. The surplus is projected to stand at 4.6 percent this \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. \par \par \uc2  Domestic demand contraction and the rupiah's real depreciation helped swing the current account into surplus, the bank said. \par \par \uc2  In the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector, the bank said, Indonesia should continue with its expansionary \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to stimulate demand. \par \par \uc2  Consequently, the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  will remain high, at 4.8 percent of GDP in 1999/2000 and 3.5 percent the following year, compared to 4.7 percent in the current year. \par \par \uc2  This will result in increasing external financing needs for the country. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia, the bank said, would need about $15 billion in the 1998/1999 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year and in each of the next four years for amortization payments of both \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and private external debt. \par \par \uc2  The bank has committed to providing $4.9 billion in the three-year period 1998 through 2000, including $3.2 billion in adjustment lending to help finance government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  needs and $1.7 billion in investment lending. \par \par \uc2  With the new loans, Indonesia is projected to near the bank's concentration limit of $13.5 billion for a single large borrower for the 2000/2002 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  years. It would limit the scope for additional lending in the future to about $1.2 to $1.3 billion a year. \par \par \uc2  The bank noted the government of President B.J. Habibie continued to show its commitment to reform. The government has attained "important achievements" in import-export \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms, domestic market deregulation and investment policies changes and improved forest management regulations. \par \par \uc2  It noted the government has also initiated several other measures, including anticorruption actions, civil service reforms, \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  decentralization and judicial reforms. \par \par \uc2  However, it warned the government could become increasingly focused on short-term measures before the June 7 general election. \par \par \uc2  "There is a danger, of course, that these initiatives may be motivated by short-term political considerations to the detriment of longer-term development objectives, and they will require close monitoring and intensive, constructive involvement by the bank and others," it said. \par \par \uc2  The election is touted as the first free and fair election in three decades. \par \par \uc2  The poll and presidential election in November could fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and stall government decision-making, the bank said. (rei/rid) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv3b007y1\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298