\par\par \b \uc2  Poor security, civil unrest still disrupt RI food supply. \b0\par\par\uc2 745 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 April 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  10 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Indonesia's food supply continues to be affected by poor security, the escalation of civil unrest as well as general \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems, international observers have said. \par \par \uc2  The Food and Agricultural Organization (FAO) and the World Food Program (WFP) found in their recent crop and supply assessment mission to Indonesia indications that markets were failing because traders were reluctant to hold stock or transport large consignments due to security concerns. \par \par \uc2  They said such failures, together with the diminished role of the State Logistics Agency (Bulog), had led to considerable variation in supplies and prices across the country, further restricting the access of the poor to markets. \par \par \uc2  "In general, while there are expectations of some recovery in agriculture and \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  this year, the longer-term prospect for employment and growth remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," they said in their report. \par \par \uc2  The assessment was conducted from March 15 to March 25 to assess current food production and evaluate overall food supply in response to growing concern over food insecurity resulting from the prolonged \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  turmoil. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in Indonesia, which began in mid-1997 with the collapse of the rupiah against the U.S. dollar and deepening liquidity problems in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as confidence in the financial sector declined, has greatly increased the vulnerability of a large segment of the population to food insecurity. \par \par \uc2  This lead to a 15 percent contraction in the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 1998, from a position of favorable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 1996 when GDP grew at 8 percent. \par \par \uc2  FAO and WFP said the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis had mainly affected food security in urban areas, with job losses and a consequent decline in household incomes and access to food. \par \par \uc2  However, the problem is spreading to rural areas as job competition is becoming fiercer and wages continue to drop, causing a further increase of migration to the already economically troubled urban areas, they said. \par \par \uc2  In urban areas, despite prospects of modest recovery this year, large segments of the population remain severely exposed to food insecurity as their ability to cope has been heavily eroded, they added. \par \par \uc2  "Although national and international measures are being taken to stimulate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, which is the solution to food insecurity in Indonesia, the benefits are, however, unlikely to be felt in the short term," the two organizations said. \par \par \uc2  They highlighted that the primary target for food assistance to the country should be children under five and expectant and lactating mothers in urban areas. \par \par \uc2  Promising \par \par \uc2  Based on the mission's field trips to main rice production areas in Java, the two organizations predicted promising rice production in 1999. \par \par \uc2  They projected that the main harvest would be good, with the support of attractive prices and favorable rainfall. \par \par \uc2  Due to the continuation of the La Nia weather pattern, an above normal rainfall is expected during the dry season, they added. The planting session begins in May. \par \par \uc2  They said the government's efforts in supplying subsidized credit and ensuring greater availability of input through support to the private sector would stimulate this year's food production. \par \par \uc2  According to the Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS), 1999's unhusked rice production is projected to reach 48.6 million metric tons, similar to its final estimate of 48.5 million tons for 1998 production. \par \par \uc2  Consequently, an estimated 3.1 million tons of rice will have to be imported during the 1999/2000 period. About 1.3 million tons of the 3.1 million import requirement is financed by commercial and soft loans and food aid. \par \par \uc2  BPS said the 1.8-million ton rice \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be covered by commercial or concessional imports, loans, grants and targeted food aid. \par \par \uc2  In addition to rice, a 3.3-million ton demand in wheat is predicted for the 1999/2000 period amid the steady decline projected in the level of wheat utilization due to lower income and demand of wheat-based products. \par \par \uc2  BPS estimates the uncovered import requirement for wheat to be 2.2 million tons for the same period. \par \par \uc2  In view of food availability and cost considerations, both organizations recommended international assistance to provide wheat-based products, such as noodles and blended foods, in association with local manufacturers. \par \par \uc2  They added that proposals also should be considered to provide additional support to the government's ongoing special market operation (OPK) program, which aims to provide subsidized rice to approximately 19 million families during the 1999/2000 period. (cst) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv4c00822\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
