\par\par \b \uc2  P&O Australia tipped for stake in local port. \b0\par\par\uc2 500 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 April 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Port operator Peninsular and Oriental Australia Ltd. is the tentative winner of a 49 percent stake in a state-owned container terminal in Surabaya, the country's second largest city, according to a senior government official. \par \par \uc2  Assistant to the State Minister of the Empowerment of State Enterprises, Sofyan Djalil, said on Monday that P&O Australia offered more than US$170 million for the stake in PT Terminal Peti Kemas Surabaya. \par \par \uc2  "But it's not final yet. There are certain technical details yet to be finalized," Sofyan told The Jakarta Post by phone from Melbourne. \par \par \uc2  He said the final deal would be announced this week. \par \par \uc2  The sale of Terminal Peti Kemas Indonesia, a 100 percent subsidiary of port operator PT Pelindo III, is the country's first privatization deal in the 1999/2000 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year starting April. \par \par \uc2  State Minister of the Empowerment of State Enterprises Tanri Abeng said that the government expected about Rp 13 trillion ($1.5 billion) in privatization proceeds in the current \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. \par \par \uc2  Four foreign port operators participated in the bidding for a 49 percent stake in the Surabaya container terminal with a 20-year concession contract. \par \par \uc2  Apart from P&O Australia, they were Stevedoring Services of America, International Container Terminal Services Inc. of the Philippines and France's Port of Marseille. \par \par \uc2  The government in March sold 51 percent in the Jakarta International Terminal Container (JICT) to port operator Grosbeak Ltd, a unit of Hong Kong conglomerate Hutchison Whampoa, for $215 million in cash. \par \par \uc2  It was the second and last privatization deal the government made during the 1998/1999 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year ending in March, raising only $395 million from the target of $1 billion. \par \par \uc2  The government earlier sold 14 percent of publicly listed cementmaker PT Semen Gresik to Mexico's Cemex SA de CV for $121 million, and another $59 million from its divestment measure in privately run PT Indofood Sukses Makmur, the world's largest instant noodle maker. \par \par \uc2  The government last week sold its remaining 4.72 percent interest in the publicly listed Indofood, raising $60 million as part of the privatization program. \par \par \uc2  Together with the P&O Australia deal, the total privatization proceeds raised in the current \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year amount to more than $230 million. \par \par \uc2  Herwidayatmo, another assistant to Tanri, earlier said "political reasons" were behind the government's decision not to sell a majority stake in Pelindo III unit. He did not elaborate. \par \par \uc2  Tanri earlier received criticism over the privatization of Pelindo II, with some claiming the selling price of JICT to Hutchison Whampoa was too low. \par \par \uc2  Tanri denied the allegation and said the government received a good price considering the current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The government plans to make divestment in several listed state-owned companies as part of its privatization program, including international telecommunications provider PT Indosat, coal mining company PT Aneka Tambang and plantations firm PT Perkebunan IV. (rei) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv4r008a6\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
