\par\par \b \uc2  Taiwanese businessmen worried about RI security. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Sylvia Gratia M. Nirang. \par \uc2 644 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 May 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  TAIPEI (JP): Worried Taiwanese businessmen called on the Indonesian government on Friday to give them special protection in doing business in the crisis-hit country. \par \par \uc2  "Our main fear is about our personal and investment security in Indonesia," one of the Taiwanese businessmen said at a seminar on Indonesian trade and investment. \par \par \uc2  The businessmen said they preferred investing in other countries if the Indonesian government could not guarantee them safety. \par \par \uc2  Another participant at the seminar held by the Indonesian Trade and Investment Mission to Taiwan and the China External Trade Development Council doubted President B.J. Habibie shared their concerns. \par \par \uc2  The investor, who asked for anonymity, said Habibie should at least provide legal grounds to protect their businesses. \par \par \uc2  Indonesians of Chinese descent are often the victims of social and ethnic violence in the country. They account for only 4 percent of the country's population but control over 60 percent of the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Rising social tension and attacks on ethnic Chinese during the unrest which has hit Indonesia since May last year has caused fear among ethnic Chinese from other countries. \par \par \uc2  Hundreds of ethnic Chinese, including Taiwanese, fled Indonesia during last year's May riots, during which hundreds of properties, including stores and office buildings, were burned and looted. \par \par \uc2  The Taiwanese businessmen said Indonesia should issue a \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  to protect ethnic Chinese investors. \par \par \uc2  The chief of the Indonesian Trade and Investment Mission, Rahardi Ramelan, said Indonesia had signed an investment protection agreement with 27 countries, including Taiwan, in order to encourage foreign investors to enter Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Under the agreement, the Indonesian government guarantees investments made by investors from these 27 countries from any damage and loss caused by riots, revolution and nationalization, he said. \par \par \uc2  "With this agreement we are protecting investments made by Taiwanese investors," he said. \par \par \uc2  Rahardi said that no matter who leads Indonesia after the upcoming presidential election, the government would uphold the law. \par \par \uc2  "Indonesia is undergoing a process of fully enforcing law and order. All kinds of political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  matters are covered by laws. So you don't need to be afraid because we will ensure that the laws are implemented fairly," he said. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, Taiwan's Deputy Director General of Industry and Development at the Ministry of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs, Shih-Chao Cho, urged businesspeople from his country to take a lead in investing in Indonesia to help the latter recover from the crisis. \par \par \uc2  "We see that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis has made Indonesia a very attractive place for investment. There are so many opportunities in the country," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said that because of recent reforms in Indonesia, opportunities had opened up for Taiwanese firms to invest or form partnerships or joint ventures in a number of areas. \par \par \uc2  "But Taiwanese businesses needs to realize that these opportunities won't be there forever. There are other investors equally interested in working with Indonesia, and we need to seize the opportunity before the window of opportunity closes on our fingers," he told more than 150 businessmen from both countries. \par \par \uc2  Cho expressed optimism that new Taiwanese businesses would eventually come to Indonesia once the current political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  were resolved. \par \par \uc2  He said the Taiwanese government and businesses had strong faith in Indonesia and were confident in the country's long-term outlook. \par \par \uc2  He said Taiwanese investment in Indonesia had slowed during the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, but he believed it would increase following the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  Cho added that Indonesia's banking industry had become one of the attractions for foreign investors following the government's move to lift limitations on foreign ownership. \par \par \uc2  In addition, comprehensive rationalization of the banking sector would leave only sound banks in operation. \par \par \uc2  "Many companies have to restructure their debt. They need new investment, so let's take the opportunity," he said. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv5f008vv\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Investors' buy sentiment continues. \b0\par\par\uc2 292 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 May 1999\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (Bisnis): Investors' buy sentiment on tourism stocks is expected to continue until next week. Investors continued speculation on sectoral shares with high gain potential. \par \par \uc2  Speculative buys by investors raised the tourism index by 5.6% to 86.03, up from 81.46. The composite index strengthened 4.5%, from 548.241 to 273.230. \par \par \uc2  Of nine sectoral stocks, three gain, three lost and other three unchanged. The total tourism shares traded reached 17.217 mln shares worth Rp 4.086. The liquidity of the tourism shares improved although not significant. \par \par \uc2  This goes in line with the macro condition of the Jakarta stock exchange. Investors welcomed the improving condition of the bourse by going after tourism stocks. \par \par \uc2  Investors' interest in buying sectoral shares improved despite \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the national tourism business. National \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  figures have also lately boosted investors' interest to invest in tourism sector. That includes the relaxation of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  interest to 31% and lower monthly inflation and the strengthening of rupiah against the USD. \par \par \uc2  The recovery of the macro \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators did help revive investors' confidence in tourism stocks on the market. \par \par \uc2  Even so, market players expressed hope that the campaign that will start on May will run smoothly and peacefully. A stable security situation will attract foreign investors into Indonesia. Whatever the reason, the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  requires a security for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to improve. \par \par \uc2  Investors are clearly cautious in finding out various possibilities in the coming campaign period. That attitude from investors is well visible from low trading on the bourse. They were not certain to take any further position on the bourse. They only made selective buys on several shares as they went on profit-taking. \par \par \uc2  * Sigma Research Inc. \par \par \uc2  (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010901dv5f000kx\par }\page {\par\fs20\b  \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia \highlight\uc2  cuts interest rate to 31%. \b0\par\par\uc2 281 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 May 1999\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  has cut the \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  for one-month deposits that come under the government guarantee to 31% for May 17-May 23 period. \par \par \uc2  Budi Mulya, a deputy to the BI Governor bureau, said BI lowered the rates by 150 points, from 32.5% to 31%. \par \par \uc2  "In the meantime, deposits for three to 24 months have also lowered. The interests for three-month deposits lowered to 29.5%, down from 31%. For three months at 28%, down from 30%. Deposits for 12 and 24 months dropped from 27% and 29% to 22% and 23% respectively. \par \par \uc2  The drop, he said, also applies to deposits and savings in US dollar, down by 50 points. "For one-month dollar deposit, the interest stands at 9.5%, down from 10%. For three months, 12 and 24 months at 8.5%," he said. \par \par \uc2  BI director Subarjo Joyosumarto said negative spread is expected to end at the end of this month. "At present \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  have all dropped." He said if \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  continue to drop until the 25% level there will be no more talk of negative spread. \par \par \uc2  Subarjo said he expects the \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  certificates (SBI) \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  to reach 20-25% at the end of this year. "For sure, the macro \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation is full of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . We cannot depend only on interest but also on the stabilizing rupiah." \par \par \uc2  If inflation stabilizes, the \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  could go down to 20% level at the end of the year. "If inflation stabilizes to the present level, I am sure the \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  would touch 20% by the end of this year," said Subarjo. (17). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010901dv5f000l1\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal