\par\par \b \uc2  Shoe firms warn of dangers of general election unrest. \b0\par\par\uc2 560 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 May 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Footwear exporters warned on Wednesday that a disruptive general election and continuing political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  could scare away foreign buyers. \par \par \uc2  The secretary-general of the Indonesian Footwear Association, Djimanto, said most foreign buyers were playing a wait-and-see attitude. \par \par \uc2  "If the general election runs smoothly, we will see a sharp increase in foreign orders. However, if not, we will see our exports continue to decline just like last year," he told `The Jakarta Post'. \par \par \uc2  Djimanto said shoe exports reached US$525 million during the first five months of this year, about the same level in the corresponding period last year. \par \par \uc2  Shoe orders began to decline sharply after riots broke out in May 1998, which led to the resignation of the long-serving ruler Soeharto. \par \par \uc2  Buyers of locally produced shoes feared political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the country would affect production and delivery. \par \par \uc2  "Shoes are fashion and seasonal goods. If they are delivered late, they are of no use anymore." \par \par \uc2  Buyers normally place orders three months before the delivery date. \par \par \uc2  Because of the unstable domestic situation, foreign buyers had taken their business to China and Vietnam, he said. \par \par \uc2  "It is ironic that, when our products are $2 or 20 percent cheaper than China's, our greatest competitor, we cannot use that opportunity. \par \par \uc2  "We can't take advantage of our export competitiveness resulting from the rupiah's sharp depreciation, due to domestic political instability." \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's shoe exports dropped from $2.2 billion in 1996 to $1.9 billion in 1997 when the regional \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis started to be felt. The figure dropped again by 37 percent to $1.2 billion in 1998. \par \par \uc2  This year, shoe exports are expected to top $1.2 billion, the same level as last year's, but this figure is dependent on the country's political and security situation, Djimanto said. \par \par \uc2  The country's four major brand shoe producers - Nike, Reebok, Villa and Adidas - recorded an average 50 percent fall in their subcontract orders, he said. \par \par \uc2  Local supplies for the four major shoe lines make up 72 percent of the total shoe exports. \par \par \uc2  Djimanto said shoe factories were only working at 50 percent production capacity. \par \par \uc2  "There are only three million pairs of shoes produced per month in the country now, compared to seven million pairs in a normal situation." \par \par \uc2  Djimanto said shoe exporters, as well as exporters of other non-oil and gas commodities, hoped the country's political and security situation could be restored to normal so businesses could prosper again. \par \par \uc2  "We hope this political infighting can be settled as soon as possible. \par \par \uc2  "If the country's situation returns to normal and calm (prevails), we hope we can gain at least $1.5 billion from shoe exports in the year 2000. Many foreign buyers have expressed a wish to buy more shoes from Indonesia." \par \par \uc2  Djimanto said shoe exporters had also called on the government to speed up the implementation of trade financing facilities to support local exporters. \par \par \uc2  The shoe industry also urged the government to abolish the 10 percent value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  imposed on raw materials for shoes bought from local industries. \par \par \uc2  "Abolishing a value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  will encourage local shoe-supporting industries to grow and also encourage shoe producers to buy locally produced raw materials and reduce imports," he said. (gis) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv5k0093p\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  SBI rate down to 27.88%. \b0\par\par\uc2 550 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 May 1999\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Rates of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's one-month term Promissory Notes (SBI) is cut 211 basis points to 27.88% this week while the rupiah was closed lower Rp135 against the greenback yesterday. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Bureau Deputy Chief Budi Mulya said the average result of one-month SBI rate auctioned on May 19, 1999 is 27.88%, down from 29.99% last week. \par \par \uc2  "The auction [SBI 1 month rate] absorbed Rp15.32 trillion or 84.35% from the amount received by BI," Mulya stated in a press release obtained by Bisnis on Wednesday. \par \par \uc2  Mulya lamented the downtrend of the \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  is in line with the declining inflation rates. The relatively stable rupiah also influenced the SBI rate cut. "This development will support the implementation of banking restructuring and will provide more space for the business sector." \par \par \uc2  The result of the SBI auction is in accordance with the prediction of BI Deputy Governor Miranda Swaray Goeltom. "The SBI rates will go down 100 to 200 basis points this week or will reach the 27% level." \par \par \uc2  Goeltom emphasized the rates will continue to be cut until the election. \par \par \uc2  "The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue to cut the rates before the election. This is an effort to speed up the recovery of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . We will try to reduce inflation pressures from the monetary aspect and supply of goods. We will continue to cut down the rates," Goeltom said in a seminar on BI bill in Jakarta on Tuesday. \par \par \uc2  The SBI rates will be cut on every chance. "Most important now is the confidence on the policies we take and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continue to grow." \par \par \uc2  Rupiah weakens \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, the rupiah closed lower Rp135 (1.69%) to Rp8,030 at the Jakarta market as an impact from the weakening regional currencies. \par \par \uc2  "The start of the campaign worry investors that it triggered dollar buying actions in the market. The weakening rupiah is also due to the strengthening of the US dollar against regional currencies," she said. \par \par \uc2  Dow Jones Market Quotes data indicated the rupiah was closed at Rp 8,030 per US dollar, down from Rp 7.895 on Tuesday. The dollar was traded at the range of Rp 7,800 to Rp 8,075. The position of the rupiah at the international market (at 7.30 p.m.) almost did not experience any changes. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not sell the dollar if rupiah weakens. "It is very unwise to react at a time like this. BI will not sell the dollar to deal with political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  during the campaigning period and pre election." \par \par \uc2  Goeltom said there is no indication of dollar buying actions in a large amount in the capital market. \par \par \uc2  "Should there be someone buying the dollar in a large amount for the sake of speculation and without the right calculation, he will suffer a loss," she said. \par \par \uc2  The problem is, she added, market expectation sees a strengthening rupiah in the next three months. "For example, based on the swap indication, the dollar will experience a downtrend against the rupiah in the next three months." \par \par \uc2  US$-Rp swap premium at the regional market, especially in Singapore, is reported continuing sliding indicating that the \b \highlight22