\par\par \b \uc2  Government comes under fire on 'reward' for DPR members. \b0\par\par\uc2 731 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 June 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): A prominent member of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  from the United Development Party (PPP) on Sunday expressed his opposition to President B.J. Habibie's plan to give a "token of gratitude", worth Rp 150 million (US$18,750), to each of the 500 House members. \par \par \uc2  Faisal Baasir, who is the deputy chairman of PPP, told 'The Jakarta Post' that the President's plan, revealed on Saturday evening by National Mandate Party (PAN) chairman Amien Rais, would disgrace the House members. \par \par \uc2  "If the government intends to give the money as a reward for our achievements, it will only humiliate the legislators," Baasir said. \par \par \uc2  According to him, the House members were chosen by people and were carrying out the people's mandate, therefore only the people deserved the reward. \par \par \uc2  "The value of the token gift from the government is nothing, considering our service to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he said. \par \par \uc2  Baasir suggested Habibie give them certificates as a reward for their work. \par \par \uc2  He proposed that the fund allocated for the "token of gratitude", which totaled Rp 75 billion, could be distributed to the 48 competing political parties. \par \par \uc2  The parties, he said, have spent a lot of money on recent campaigning activities. \par \par \uc2  As reported earlier, Amien told the press in his party's "post campaign" party on Saturday that he had a copy of a decree signed by Habibie expressing his gratitude for the hard work of the 500 legislators. \par \par \uc2  As a "token of gratitude", Amien said quoting the letter, Habibie would present Rp 150 million to each of the House members. \par \par \uc2  As of Sunday evening, none of Habibie's officials could be reached to comment on the plan, which is said by Amien to be stipulated in presidential decree 47/1999, dated May 20. \par \par \uc2  No idea \par \par \uc2  On the other hand, many of the current legislators, who will end their term on Aug. 24 this year, having served in the House since 1997, claimed to have no idea about Habibie's generous plan. \par \par \uc2  Some said that they had never heard of the matter, which according to a report would be handled by the Ministry of Finance. \par \par \uc2  "We could not make a comment yet, since we don't know the essence of the decree," veteran legislator Abu Hasan Sadzili from Golkar told the 'Post'. \par \par \uc2  According to the previous schedule, the legislators, who were repeatedly asked by anti-Soeharto protesters to step down following the resignation of the former president, would end their tenure in the year 2002. \par \par \uc2  But following the fall of Soeharto, Habibie's administration decided under \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  pressure to bring forward the general election. \par \par \uc2  The new legislators will be elected based on the results of Monday's polls. \par \par \uc2  According to the existing House \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 12, issued in 1980, the current legislators would receive a retirement pension. \par \par \uc2  "For example, a legislator working for a period of five years would receive a pension of Rp 1.5 million per month," legislator Baasir said. \par \par \uc2  Therefore, he said, Habibie's "token of gratitude" would be too much for the House members. \par \par \uc2  Baasir speculated that the money, if there is no strong objection from the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 , would be transferred to the bank accounts of the legislators a few days before their last day in the House. \par \par \uc2  Amien told the press on Saturday that one of Habibie's considerations in issuing the decree was the good performance of the House members during their tenure of only two years, instead of the normal five-year period. \par \par \uc2  "They have produced various bills in line with the MPR (People's Consultative Assembly) decrees and the agreements between the government and the International Monetary Fund (IMF)," Amien quoted a copy of Habibie's presidential decree as saying. \par \par \uc2  Amien said that he strongly opposed the plan. \par \par \uc2  "The fate of the workers of the food and candy manufacturers PT Mayora remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and this is so for many people," he said, referring to hundreds of Mayora workers who staged a noisy protest here last week, demanding the company reemploy them after they were dismissed late April. \par \par \uc2  PAN secretary-general Faisal Basri echoed his party chairman's statement, saying that Habibie's government had no sense of crisis. \par \par \uc2  "Our people are facing \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  hardship but still the government seems not to care about it," he told the 'Post'. (asa/bsr) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv67009n2\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Election peaceful, rupiah on the rise. \b0\par\par\uc2 581 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 June 1999\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The rupiah yesterday ended stronger against the dollar by 380 points (4.92%) at 7,725 in foreign markets, in the wake of peaceful elections. \par \par \uc2  "The rupiah yesterday recorded its largest gain against the US$ since last December. \par \par \uc2  The peaceful elections provided a positive sentiment for the rupiah," said a US bank dealer in Singapore, as quoted by the Dow Jones. \par \par \uc2  Dow Jones Market Quotes reported that the rupiah ended at 7,725 per dollar, up from 8,105 last week. \par \par \uc2  The dollar was traded at the Rp7,980-Rp7,700 range and stabilized at Rp7,725/US$. \par \par \uc2  The dealer added that market players let go their long dollar position after the election took place peacefully. \par \par \uc2  "Many players took long positions before the elections. But as there were no riots, many of them sold their US$." \par \par \uc2  The dealer predicted that the rupiah would continue to strengthen to 7,000, "even 6,500." \par \par \uc2  Other dealers, however, disagreed. \par \par \uc2  "It's too optimistic. The rise of the rupiah today [yesterday] is inseparable from the fact that the forex market was closed because Monday was a national day." \par \par \uc2  A European bank dealer on Singapore said that if the opposition wins the election, the rupiah would continue to rise. \par \par \uc2  "Many foreign players abandoned their long dollar position. They are convinced that the rupiah would rise if the opposition wins," he told Reuters. \par \par \uc2  Although in the long term there will be \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies of the new government, the rupiah will continue to strengthen. \par \par \uc2  "It remains a question if the rupiah would pass the 7,000 level soon. If that happens, the rupiah enters a new era." \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, a number of analysts in London predicted that the rupiah would continue to rise until a new president is chosen in November 1999. \par \par \uc2  "Fundamentally, the rupiah is still undervalued. We are upbeat on the elections. To that end, we have no plan to alter our strategy in buying rupiah at 8,300 per dollar AS," the Banque Paribas London dealer said. \par \par \uc2  Another analyst said that the market is watching Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "Many things need to be watched beside the elections. For example, the recovery process of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  appears not too good," said Nick Douch of Barclays Capital London. \par \par \uc2  A dealer in Singapore said that players refuse to sell their rupiahs since the Indonesian Democratic Party-Struggle (PDI-P) plans to apply a fixed exchange rate in order to stabilize the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "As a party that may win the elections, the PDI-P statement on fixed exchange rate has an impact on the market." \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) governor Syahril Sabirin told CNBC Asia that a peaceful elections would lift the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  "BI would be happy to see the rupiah at 7,000/US$ to 7,500/US$." \par \par \uc2  He hoped that any party that wins the election would adhere to the IMF program. \par \par \uc2  "If not, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would face problems." \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, foreign investors last week reached a net buying of Rp518.508 billion, causing market capitalization to hit the Rp383.385 trillion mark. \par \par \uc2  The JSX composite index (IHSG) last week rose by 28.729 points (4.92%) and ended at 612.378. \par \par \uc2  PT Panin Sekuritas director Hendra H. Kustarjo said the index started to climb on Thursday after the election campaign proceeded in a relatively safe manner. \par \par \uc2  "If the situation remains safe after the elections, share trading is set to become even more buoyant." (17/shm/ind). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010901dv68000ro\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  BKPM optimistic foreign investors will return. \b0\par\par\uc2 685 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 June 1999\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The government is optimistic investors will soon return to Indonesia following the peaceful first real democratic election in 32 years. \par \par \uc2  According to the Minister for Investment/ Chairman of the National Coordinating Board of Investment (BKPM) Marzuki Usman, Indonesia will regain confidence from the investors as soon as the election result comes out. "By God's will, investments will return," he said after a coordination meeting on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and finance yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Marzuki, elaborated, the peaceful election process proves to foreign investors that democracy has taken its course and that there is law and order in Indonesia. "And whoever shall lead this country, carries a trusteeship," he said. \par \par \uc2  The government, he added, is hoping that the number of foreign investments that will soon flow into Indonesia is equal to the ones before the crisis, like in early 1997. He cited South Korea has already pocketed US$5.6 billion in foreign investments in a short period. \par \par \uc2  IMF renegotiation \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, PAU Chairman on \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Studies from UGM Anggito Abimanyu suggested the winning party to renegotiate some issues with the IMF. \par \par \uc2  According to him, the new government needs to renegotiate a number of programs that have been agreed with between the current government and the IMF. \par \par \uc2  "Renegotiation of a number of programs with the IMF is necessary, especially concerning privatization," he told Bisnis via e-mail from Melbourne, Australia, yesterday. \par \par \uc2  According to him, the privatization program of some state firms have to be renegotiated because the execution schedule is irrational and is difficult to meet. \par \par \uc2  "Moreover, renegotiations on \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the social safety net program and banking restructuring are also necessary," he added. \par \par \uc2  Despite the already low 27% \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  today, he suggested it needs to be lowered more to give a wider space to the business sector. \par \par \uc2  In the banking restructuring, he added, the process has to be conducted prudently and transparently, especially on banking financial diclosures. \par \par \uc2  On the election, Abimanyu said although foreigners are still \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  with Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  future but they will cheer should the election is won by pro-reform parties. \par \par \uc2  "Foreigners are pessimistic and jittery if Golkar and its status-quo party wins the election," he said. \par \par \uc2  Until yesterday, pro reform parties (PDI-P, PKB and PAN) have already left the status-quo party far behind in the vote count. \par \par \uc2  Foreigners are generally no longer concerned with the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  potential "Those that already invested here have no other choice than to maintain them. But they are concerned if the status-quo returns to power." \par \par \uc2  In 1998, Marzuki said Indonesia suffered a significant decline in investments. He cited the MM-2000 industrial area in Bekasi, only realized one factory and also one factory this year. But he is optimistic the situation will recover. \par \par \uc2  Before the June 7 election took place, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  observer James W. Castle said investors were waiting for the result of the election before they decide to return to Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  According to him, investors wanted to see a smooth election process before returning to Indonesia. "If the process went wrong, whoever wins is not valid. And therefore, investors wanted to wait and see how the process goes," he said. \par \par \uc2  Previously, BKPM disclosed the approval of a number of foreign investments (PMA) during the 16 April-15 May 1999 period that reached US$584.9 million or up 53.79% compared to the previous period, of which only stood at US$380 million. \par \par \uc2  Besides the increasing investment value, BKPM data also revealed an increasing number of projects. Between 16 April-15 May 1999 the number of PMA projects approved by the government reached 97, while only 92 project in the previous months. \par \par \uc2  Domestic (PMDN) projects, however, fell sharply by 62.45%. Domestic projects in the previous months reached Rp1,598 trillion (17 projects), while in April-May only Rp 600 billion [17 projects]. \par \par \uc2  As a whole, the total number of investments approved by BKPM between 16 April-15 May 1999 were 114. The figure is up by 4.4% compared to the previous months of only 109 approvals. (k8/ab). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010901dv6900137\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
