\par\par \b \uc2  Parties need conditional accord. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,047 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 June 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The following is the second of two articles on Indonesian post-election politics written by Yulius P. Hermawan, a lecturer on international relations at Parahyangan Catholic University and a researcher at the Parahyangan Center for International Studies in Bandung, West Java. He is a graduate of the Department of Politics, Monash University, Australia. \par \par \uc2  BANDUNG (JP): As there is still \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  on who will govern the country, the role of major parties is now very important in securing the route to political stability. \par \par \uc2  What should major parties do to guarantee political stability? The formation of coalition parties will probably help secure stability in the near future. \par \par \uc2  However, if it is hard for major parties to consider the formation of a coalition party as the best alternative for the long-term future of Indonesian politics, a conditional bargaining between eligible parties may be one alternative which could help build a new political platform as well as political stability. \par \par \uc2  Conditional bargaining is a common phenomenon in a new democracy. It is necessary since there is no clear-cut rule in securing stable competition among independent parties, while the result of competition is unpredictable. Rational compromise among parties are then necessary to form a certain stable system which may guarantee an order. \par \par \uc2  This must be built on an assumption that all parties are responsible for establishing a new political platform on which democracy will really take place. In return for responsibility, the platform will benefit them in the future, giving all partisans the same chance to hold power. \par \par \uc2  The conditional bargaining among parties will produce an alliance which encourages parties to achieve goals - to seek office as well as to pursue certain policies. It may encourage parties to form a collective leadership if parties consider a coalition government as a necessary condition. Sharing the governmental office would be a good alternative condition. As part of the coalition government, each party would have to support the initiatives of the leading party under acceptable conditions. However, the coalition government does not necessarily mean that parties should be engaged to form a coalition party under one banner. Each party is still an independent organization which has the same chance to win the next \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  competition. \par \par \uc2  There are two crucial dimensions which all partisans should consider to participate in conditional bargaining. \par \par \uc2  The first dimension is the quest for acknowledging the significance of the general election for the birth of a new credible leadership. All party leaders should respect the general election as the most acceptable reference to the people's collective choice. They should recognize the decision on new leadership should consider the popular mandate given through the general election. Any decision reached in the MPR should be in accordance with the popular mandate. It is very important because eligible voters will finally accept the new leadership so long as the MPR considers the collective choice was shown in a fair and honest election. \par \par \uc2  This dimension will bring some crucial consequences. There should be a general agreement among parties on the superiority of a certain party. Whoever gets the most respectable number of votes will hold political superiority in leading the formation of a new government. The other parties will not force or hinder the superior party to call for alliance with some parties to form the government. \par \par \uc2  Parties which lost in the last election should respect the conditional superiority to produce decisions, in return for a political guarantee that they may take over the government through the next \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  competition and, hence, may produce decisions in the future if they win the competition. Any candidate whose party failed to win superiority should agree that their candidacy will lack legitimacy. The last point will lead those candidates to reconsider their ambitions to be elected and to perform rationally in the decision-making processes. \par \par \uc2  Secondly, all parties should accept that the main task of the new regime is to put out clear-cut fundamentals of the Indonesian political system. The system needs to transform into somewhat of an establishment. According to the Constitution, Indonesia adopts the presidential system. However, the past regime rejected the classical theory of democracy where people directly elected a leader (president). \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, past leaders were also reluctant to claim that Indonesia adopts a liberal democracy where eligible voters held a determinant right to elect representatives who would be responsible for generating substantially superior decisions through an intensively open debate among themselves. The last election gives simple, but good lessons about difficulties on how to elect legitimate leadership due to the unclear principles of the system. \par \par \uc2  The new regime will also have a necessary task to solve the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, to correct the wrongdoings of the past regime and to conduct law reforms. To complete those responsibilities, the new leadership needs the support of all the components of the new system. \par \par \uc2  This condition will encourage both the executive and the \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  institutions to cross their fingers in order to set new principles of the system and to complete all necessary tasks. The two will 