\par\par \b \uc2  Apartment market to remain gloomy until year end. \b0\par\par\uc2 481 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 June 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Property consultants have predicted that the capital will continue to experience a decline in demand for residential apartment rental space throughout the year, and expect increased vacancy at the end of 1999. \par \par \uc2  PT Procon Indah/Jones Lang LaSalle said the dim outlook was particularly due to the continuing business contraction and company rationalization. \par \par \uc2  "Although \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators, such as GDP growth, \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and inflation, showed early signs of recovery during the first quarter of 1999, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  toward the political events in June and December remains," the company said in its latest biweekly property report. \par \par \uc2  It predicts the overall vacancy levels to increase to 45 percent by the end of 1999 and to reach 48 percent by the end of 2000. \par \par \uc2  A slight rebound is expected to occur at the end of 2001 as a result of positive \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2000 and 2001, which would generate new demand and limited new supply in the market, the company said. \par \par \uc2  Weak demand and higher vacancy by 2000 would increase pressure on landlords to reduce rental rates. \par \par \uc2  The report said total occupied apartments declined by 108 units during the first quarter of 1999, due to weakened demand resulting by the shrinking expatriate population amid foreign companies' on-going rationalization. \par \par \uc2  Total vacancies during the period was 5,859 units, reflecting an increase of 2.3 percent over the quarter. The average vacancy level was 42 percent as at March this year. \par \par \uc2  Weakened demand for rental apartments have forced developers to further reduce rental rates or offer other incentives to secure new tenants. \par \par \uc2  More apartment owners now offer shorter lease terms or a minimum of six months with quarterly payments. They previously offered two to three-year leases with payments in advance. \par \par \uc2  Some landlords have even started to offer existing tenants monthly lease extensions in a bid to maintain occupancy levels. \par \par \uc2  Most owners of prime apartments continued to offer rents in U.S. dollars, but with discounts of up to 60 percent following the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  The company predicted apartment rentals to bottom out in 2000 and grow modestly in late 2001 as demand was expected to rebound. \par \par \uc2  Total stocks now stand at 13,984 units, a figure reflecting a 6.2 increase from last year, according to the report. \par \par \uc2  It said no new projects were completed during the first five months of the year, in line with the generally sluggish construction activities during the period. \par \par \uc2  All construction work is expected to be suspended until the general election process is concluded. \par \par \uc2  The supply of purpose-built rental apartments, including serviced apartments and rental townhouses, remained at 5,786 units as of May. \par \par \uc2  It is estimated that 1,189 rental apartment units would enter the market by 2001, about 68 percent of which would come from individual condominiums available for lease. (cst) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv6i009yu\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  IMF - The rupiah can still rise. \b0\par\par\uc2 454 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 June 1999\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Deputy Managing Director of the IMF Stanley Fischer said that the rupiah can still go up. \par \par \uc2  He made the statement after meeting with President B.J.Habibie for three hours at Merdeka Palace here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Fischer welcomed the rupiah's rise which he attributed to a.o. the smooth elections. \par \par \uc2  He said it would help restore \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  confidence in the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "Political stability will help the rupiah to strengthen." \par \par \uc2  The rupiah yesterday went down slightly, in the wake of political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  here. \par \par \uc2  Dow Jones New Wires said the rupiah ended at 7,295 per dollar, down 22 points (0.30%) from 7,273 on Thursday. \par \par \uc2  Separately, C. Harinowo, a member of the IMF board, said the swift rise of the rupiah could endanger the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as it makes Indonesian products less competitive in the international market. \par \par \uc2  "The rupiah still has room to strengthen, as long as it does not do so too swiftly. It's better to be late but sure," Harinowo said here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Huber Neiss, the Asia-Pacific director of the IMF, also said that the rupiah can still appreciate as the currency has been too low for long. \par \par \uc2  BI governor Syahril Sabirin had earlier predicted that the rupiah could at the most rise to 6,000 against the US dollar. \par \par \uc2  Syahril added that to be stronger than 6,000 would be difficult as inflation in 1998 was very high. \par \par \uc2  On the forex system, Fischer said that "I do not wish to discuss the issue. But a fixed rate system is difficult to maintain as certain conditions must be in place." \par \par \uc2  "Moreover, the current floating system is doing well. Now is not the right time to change the system." \par \par \uc2  However, he added, the IMF plans to discuss the issue with PDIP's Kwik Kian Gie, who once proposed the fixed rate system. \par \par \uc2  IMF, added Fischer, has also pressed the government to speed up banking and corporate debt restructuring. \par \par \uc2  He said both schemes are proceeding slowly and as such must be speeded up. \par \par \uc2  Separately, senior economics minister Ginandjar Kartasasmita admitted that the IMF had called on the government to look closely into the two matters. \par \par \uc2  "They have asked us to increase efforts to go after corporate debts," said Ginadjar. \par \par \uc2  He said such efforts would help the government reduce the burden carried by the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which has to bear bond interest payment to recapitalize banks worth Rp17 trillion. \par \par \uc2  Ginandjar said that the government plans to adhere to the schedule agreed with the IMF. \par \par \uc2  BPPN, for example, has set a deadline of end of June 1999 for large bad debtors to sign letters indicating their ability to settle their debts. (dj/ab/ens). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1999 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010901dv6j0014p\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
